mturk_id:
To confirm that you are a human being, and not a robot, please enter your MTurk ID number in the box below. 



You can find this number by going to the "Your Account" tab at the top of the MTurk screen. Directly under "Your Account", click on "Dashboard". At the top of your personal "Dashboard" you will see "Dashboard - your name" and your "Worker ID". Your worker ID is clearly marked; it is a series of letters and numbers written in orange text.

debrief_1: At first I thought maybe you were testing how we feel or react to getting answers right or wrong. Then as I was doing it I thought maybe you were trying to see if we could figure out a pattern or not.
debrief_2: Yes, at first I had to do a several test clicks and see if there was anything I could pick up about the differences in the people. I didn't see anything. So I clicked until I found the right one and then would keep clicking on them until it was wrong, and then I would move to another person until I found the right one again. A few times I didn't even follow my own pattern, but just went with what felt right or if it "seemed" like it was going to change people. Sometimes that strategy worked! And sometimes it did not, so I went back to just clicking until it was wrong, finding the right one again, and clicking until they were then wrong.
debrief_3: Yes, I tried several different methods. I even tried to wait it out and see if anything happened to the people if I gave it some time. I didn't see anything and feared running out of time, so I kept going. I also tried to go fast, wondering if the answer would always be right if someone was clicked within a certain amount of time. That also did not work. So I went with the only thing that made sense, which was finding the one that gave +100 and sticking with them until they became a -50 and then moving on until the +100 was found again.

feedback:
Oh dear... I spent so long trying to think out that last questions that I lost track of what we were actually focusing on in this survey! Clearly I have a problem moving on when I do not have a reasonable answer for a question. Maybe that will provide you some more insight into who I am. 

Also just a heads up, when asking our opinions about political figures, you spelled the name "Macro Rubio". I assume you meant Marco Rubio, but I selected "not applicable" because I never know what these things are actually testing us on, and didn't want to give an opinion on someone who doesn't exist.

I would be very curious to know if there was some kind of pattern for the game. Anything other than total randomness. Or was it staged to purposely give wrong answers at certain intervals? Was there ever a chance at doing well at this game? I'd love to know the answers to these questions and find out more about the work that you are doing. How exactly that relates to my psychological well-being, and why you asked to know the medications I am on.

I suppose I will clarify on that, all of those have been prescribed to me after an acute aortic dissection. So, the frequent thoughts of death is not something that is really out of line for me. I'm on borrowed time as it is, as I would have been dead 3 years ago without modern medicine.

So, please keep that in mind when looking over my medical history and the questions related to that. The severe fatigue and anxiety is likely all wrapped up within my physical ailments, as well as the byproduct of the human brain knowing it's dodged death but could be hanging around any corner up ahead.

I wish you the very best of luck with your research and hope you find the data you are looking for! Thank you for allowing me to participate!

debrief_2: If I got a 100 with a person, I would stick with them until I got two consecutive -50 scores. This let me know the "ideal person" had transitioned to someone else, so I clicked on the other people until I found a +100, and stuck with them again until seeing two consecutive -50s.
debrief_3: I started out by switching when I saw one -50, but I quickly realized even the good students failed about 20% of the time.
